    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-02-18T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-02-18T08:00:00-05:00" n="195"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d195">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51W89 U.S.S.R./185: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_WJC1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wiley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-02-18T16:00:00+03:00"
                            >February 18, 1935—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 18—11:51 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>71. My 56, February 9, 1 p.m. Saturday afternoon<note n="13" xml:id="d195fn13"
                        >February 16.</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_LMM1">Litvinov</persName> received <persName
                        corresp="#p_DW1">Duranty</persName>. He showed him in “confidence” the
                    undated memorandum initialed by the President relative to settlement of debts
                    and claims and vigorously attacked American policy. He rejected <persName
                        corresp="#p_DW1">Duranty</persName>’s suggestion to permit publication of
                    memorandum in <hi rend="italic">New York Times</hi> but I understand that the
                    Foreign Office censorship passed a despatch from <persName corresp="#p_DW1"
                        >Duranty</persName> based on his conversation with <persName
                        corresp="#p_LMM1">Litvinov</persName> which was of a provocative nature. The
                    despatch was presumably published in the <hi rend="italic">Times</hi> this
                        morning.<note n="14" xml:id="d195fn14">
                        <hi rend="italic">New York Times</hi>, February 18, 1935, p. 1, col.
                        4.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The American correspondents are urging me to hold regular press conferences. I
                    would be grateful if the Department would indicate to me the attitude to adopt
                    when queried regarding “unpublished documents”.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WJC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Wiley</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
